get_upregulated <- function(df){
    key <- intersect(rownames(df)[which(df$log2FoldChange>=1)], rownames(df)[which(df$pvalue<=0.05)])
  results <- as.data.frame((df)[which(rownames(df) %in% key),])
    return(results)
}
get_downregulated <- function(df){
    key <- intersect(rownames(df)[which(df$log2FoldChange<=-1)], rownames(df)[which(df$pvalue<=0.05)])
    results <- as.data.frame((df)[which(rownames(df) %in% key),])
    return(results)
}
annotate_de_genes <- function(df){

    df$hgnc_symbol <- rownames(df)
    mart <- useMart(biomart = "ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")
    info <- getBM(attributes=c("hgnc_symbol",
                               "ensembl_gene_id_version",
                               "chromosome_name",
                               "start_position",
                               "end_position",
                               "strand",
                               "entrezgene_description"),
                  filters = c("hgnc_symbol"),
                  values = df$hgnc_symbol,
                  mart = mart,
                  useCache=FALSE)

    tmp <- merge(df, info, by="hgnc_symbol")
    tmp$strand <- gsub("-1", "-", tmp$strand)
    tmp$strand <- gsub("1", "+", tmp$strand)
    tmp$hgnc_symbol <- make.names(tmp$hgnc_symbol, unique = T)
    tmp <- tmp[!grepl("CHR", tmp$chromosome_name),]

    output_col <- c("Gene", "Ensembl ID", "Chromosome", "Start", "Stop", "Strand", "Description", "Log2FC", "P-value", "Adj P-value")
    tmp <- subset(tmp, select=c(hgnc_symbol, ensembl_gene_id_version, chromosome_name, start_position, end_position, strand, entrezgene_description, log2FoldChange, pvalue, padj))
    colnames(tmp) <- output_col

    if(min(tmp$Log2FC) > 0){
        tmp <- tmp[order(-tmp$Log2FC),]
    }else{
        tmp <- tmp[order(tmp$Log2FC),]
    }

    return(tmp)

}

#name: Supritha Raj #Github: https://github.com/MSuprithaRaj/Rna_seq_Analysis.git #ID: 23103608 #A crucial aspect of cancer research is the identification of Differentially Expressed Genes (DEGs) in cancer cells compared to normal cells . This report aims to interpret the connections between some of the top DEGs known to cancer biology. #Identification of DEGs: Through immense genomic analyses over the years, researchers have found several DEGs that play important roles in cancer progression. Notably, genes such as TP53, PTEN, and BRCA1 have emerged in various cancer types. The tumor suppressor gene TP53, commonly known as the guardian of the genome, is frequently mutated in cancer cells, leading to the dysregulation of cell cycle control and DNA repair mechanisms. PTEN, another crucial tumor suppressor, is frequently inactivated in various cancers, contributing to uncontrolled cell growth and survival. BRCA1, implicated in breast and ovarian cancers, is vital for maintaining genomic stability.1. TP53 and Cell Cycle Control: TP53, a critical regulator of the cell cycle, is frequently mutated in cancers. Its role in inducing cell cycle arrest and promoting DNA repair is compromised in mutated forms, leading to uncontrolled cell division. This dysregulation contributes to the formation of tumors. Moreover, TP53 mutations are associated with increased resistance to apoptosis, allowing cancer cells to evade programmed cell death mechanisms. #1. PTEN and PI3K/AKT Pathway: PTEN acts as a negative regulator of the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway, which plays a central role in cell growth and survival. Loss of PTEN function results in hyperactivation of this pathway, promoting cell proliferation and inhibiting apoptosis. The dysregulation of PI3K/AKT signaling is a common feature in many cancers, making PTEN a key player in tumorigenesis. Therapeutic strategies targeting this pathway are actively being explored in cancer treatment. #2. BRCA1 and DNA Repair Mechanisms: BRCA1 is crucial for repairing damaged DNA and maintaining genomic stability. Mutations in BRCA1 compromise the cells ability to repair DNA efficiently, leading to the accumulation of genetic abnormalities and an increased risk of cancer development. Understanding the role of BRCA1 in DNA repair has not only provided insights into the molecular basis of certain cancers but has also paved the way for targeted therapies, such as PARP inhibitors, specifically designed for BRCA-mutated tumors.
